{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508460"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.25,0.51,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"581"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2075"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a six month history of a painless swelling in his neck (Image). It has been slowly getting larger. He has no other health issues. He smokes 15 cigarettes per day (and has for 55 years) and drinks about four cans of beer a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is an immobile 6cm diameter smooth-surfaced, firm and non-tender swelling partially overlying the left mandible. Intra-oral inspection is normal, as is the rest of the physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Along with fine needle aspiration, which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line imaging investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sialogram","MRI head and neck","Contrast enhanced CT neck","Lateral neck X-ray","PET scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeck lumps represent an important presentation to GPs in the community and is often the first presenting symptom of head and neck cancer. They should be considered malignancy until this has been excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed flag symptoms for head and neck cancer include mass present for \u0026gt;2 weeks, voice change, dysphagia, weight loss, loss of appetite, nasal obstruction, loss of hearing (one sided) or epistaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for head and neck cancer include smoking, alcohol use, age \u0026gt;40, and a history of previous head and neck cutaneous lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lump in this image is in the submandibular region, there is no overlying skin changes, physical examination reveals it is firm and not mobile, and is large. It was later diagnosed as a pleomorphic adenoma of the submandibular gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst line investigation for all patients at risk of malignancy is a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT of the neck\u003C/strong\u003E with contrast and fine-needle aspiration. This helps to localise the mass, assess extension and involvement of lymph nodes, and allow staging. Ultrasound with FNA would also be a good option to visualise the lump and determine its consistency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI \u003C/strong\u003Emay be useful as an imaging method for soft tissue swelling without radiation, but a CT scan would be appropriate first in this case. MRI has limitations due to its availability, duration of scan time, tolerability and displays more motion artefact. Certainly if this was a parotid swelling, an MRI (as the definitive investigation) would provide a more detailed analysis than a CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral neck x-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would not be a useful imaging modality to further differentiate this mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esialogram \u003C/strong\u003Eis used to identify a stone blocking the salivary ducts. These often have distinct presentations of jaw pain associated with the anticipation of food. This is a non-tender swelling with no symptoms associated with food.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E PET scan\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in this case. It would help to identify if this lump was a tumour, but is not a first line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReferral to ENT would also be appropriate where simple bed-side investigations such as a nasal endoscopy can be done to identify if there is a mass in the nose that may represent a cancer has spread to the neck.\u00a0 \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFine needle aspiration can be used for cytology to determine if it is malignant. Core biopsy should not be done on neck lumps due to the risk of seeding into the skin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All neck masses should be considered malignancy until proven otherwise","If a patient has a neck lump and risk of malignancy first line investigation is contrast CT head/neck and FNA"],"references":["Jaya, J \u0026 Tan E, 2020. An approach to neck masses in adults. Australian Journal of General Practice. Vol 49, Issue 5, May 2020. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-09-19-5080"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15281"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15281"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/755e2780-06ae-4e1c-8b3f-3cf329544857.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/755e2780-06ae-4e1c-8b3f-3cf329544857.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97847"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T17:36:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T17:37:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpretin